  "doc_id": "47223",
  "text": "A distinct possibility is that effects of PKC are mediated through a parallel mechanism that affects contraction per se rather than being fundamentally involved in the myogenic signaling pathway itself. For example, PKC has been implicated as both an inhibitor (100) and an activator [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] of VGC channels in various preparations; obviously by modulating Ca 2ϩ availability PKC could influence the extent of myogenic reactivity. In re-cent studies of afferent arterioles, Kirton and Loutzenhiser [CITATION_3] have suggested that PKC modulates the activity of K v channels (48) that would indirectly potentiate myogenic contraction. This was demonstrated by the finding that the effects of PKC inhibition on attenuation of myogenic reactivity could be reversed by treatment with 4-aminopyridine, a known inhibitor of K v channels. In addition to simply acting on parallel pathways, PKC activation can possibly lead to multiple effects in one tissue; thus it has been reported that the PKC activator indolactam both enhances Ca 2ϩ current through VGC channels and enhances Ca 2ϩ sensitivity at the level of the contractile proteins [CITATION_4] .",
